            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#VM">
                <p>God, (grant) good luck. The Syracusans have decreed
                    [in favour of the inhabitants of Akrai citizenship and exemption from taxes] and the right [to own land and the right to sit in the front row (during performances)/the right to marry(?)] if they are descendants of gamoroi
                    and (have decreed) that they have the right to participate in all public offices
                    [with the exception of (that of) ... and] (that of) the hipparchus and
                    [---]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#VM">
                <p>Dio, (concedi) buona fortuna. I Siracusani hanno decretato
                    [a favore degli abitanti di Akrai la cittadinanza e l'esenzione dalle tasse] e il diritto
                    [di possesso della terra e il diritto di sedere in prima fila (durante gli spettacoli)/il diritto di contrarre matrimonio(?)] nel caso in cui siano nati da gamoroi
                    e (hanno decretato) che abbiano il diritto di partecipare a tutte le cariche pubbliche
                    [ad eccezione di (quella) de ... e] (quella) dell'ipparco e
                    [---]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en" resp="#VM">
                <p>Decree engraved on a bronze tablet in a fragmentary state found in the area of Palazzolo Acreide (ancient Akrai) 
                    in the twenties of the twentieth century and now preserved at the Metropolitan Museum in New York. 
                    The text, partially reconstructible, reports mention of a series of privileges - the politeia, the ateleia (or isoteleia), 
                    and possession of land (and house?) - granted to an individual or a group of foreign individuals who are received into 
                    the citizenship of another polis (specified in the part of the text now lost) in which the group of gamoroi - known from 
                    the sources as landowners belonging to the Syracusan aristocracy - must have had a central role, probably as a group 
                    of full citizens of the polis. The decree has been dated by most scholars between 491 and 485 on account of the episode, 
                    reported, among others, by Herodotus (Hdt. 7.155.2) of the expulsion of the gamoroi from Syracuse following the revolt 
                    of a coalition of demos and slaves (kyllyrioi). Nevertheless, from the paleographic point of view there are several elements that 
                    would allow us to date it to the end of the 6th century BC. 
                    Despite the origin of the document from the Syracusan area, 
                    the inscription uses an alphabet afferent to the 'eastern group' (in Kirchhoff's subdivision). The text is written in the Doric dialect, 
                    with traits that refer to the Corinthian Doric.</p>
            </div>
